{{pp-pc1}}
{{Same-sex unions}}
{{Use American English|date=July 2015}}  
{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}
[[File:Wedding in New Orleans, November 11, 2017.jpg|thumb|300px|Two men celebrate their marriage in the United States.]]
In the United States, [[same-sex marriage]] is legal in all states, [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]], U.S. territories except [[LGBT rights in American Samoa|American Samoa]], but not on all [[Same-sex marriage under United States tribal jurisdictions|Native American tribal lands]]. Same-sex marriage has been legal since June 26, 2015, when the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' that state-level bans on same-sex marriage are unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/videos/us/2015/06/26/supreme-court-same-sex-marriage-ruling-brown-dnt-tsr.cnn|title=U.S. 21st country to allow same-sex marriage nationwide|date=June 26, 2015|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Liptak|first1=Adam|title=Same-Sex Marriage Is a Right, Supreme Court Rules, 5-4|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/27/us/supreme-court-same-sex-marriage.html |newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Obergefell et al. v. Hodges, Director, Ohio, Department of Health, et al.|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf|website=supremecourt.gov|accessdate=June 26, 2015}}</ref> The court ruled that the denial of [[marriage license]]s to same-sex couples and the refusal to recognize those marriages performed in other jurisdictions violates the [[Substantive due process|Due Process]] and the [[Equal Protection Clause|Equal Protection]] clauses of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] of the [[United States Constitution]]. The ruling overturned a 1972 precedent, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]''. Just prior to the Supreme Court's ruling in 2015, same-sex marriage was legal in many but not all U.S. jurisdictions.

While [[civil rights]] campaigning took place from the 1970s,<ref name="Gumbel">{{cite news |last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|title=The Great Undoing?|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/06/20/great-undoing|work=[[The Advocate]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> the issue became prominent from around 1993, when the [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] ruled in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]'' that the prohibition was [[unconstitutional]]. The ruling led to federal actions and actions by several states, to restrict marriage to male-female couples, in particular the ''[[Defense of Marriage Act]]'' (DOMA). During the period of 2003 to 2015, various lower court decisions, state legislation, and popular referendums already legalized same-sex marriage to some degree in thirty-eight out of fifty [[U.S. states]], in the [[Territories of the United States|U.S. territory]] of [[Guam]], and in the [[District of Columbia]]. In 2013, the Supreme Court overturned a key provision of DOMA, declaring part of it unconstitutional and in breach of the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]] in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'' because it "single[d] out a class of persons" for discrimination, by refusing to treat their marriages equally under federal law when state law had created them equally valid. The ruling led to the Federal Government's recognition of same-sex marriage, with federal benefits for married couples connected to either the state of residence or the state in which the marriage was solemnized. However, the ruling focused on the provision of DOMA responsible for the Federal Government refusing to acknowledge state sanctioned same-sex marriages, leaving the question of state marriage laws itself to the individual states. The Supreme Court addressed that question two years later in 2015, ruling, in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges|Obergefell]]'', that same-sex married couples were to be constitutionally accorded the same recognition as opposite-sex couples at state/territory levels, as well as at federal level.

By the time that same-sex marriage became legal nationally, [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|public opinion on the subject]] reached almost 60% approval levels according to polls by ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2015/03/09/support-for-gay-marriage-hits-all-time-high-wsjnbc-news-poll/|title=Support for Gay Marriage Hits All-Time High — WSJ/NBC News Poll|author=Janet Hook|work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> the [[Human Rights Campaign]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/gay-marriage-voters-poll-115171.html|title=Poll: 60 percent of likely voters back gay marriage|work=Politico |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> and [[CNN]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2015/02/cnn-poll-63-percent-of-americans-say-same-sex-couples-have-a-right-to-marry/|title=CNN poll: 63 percent of Americans say same-sex couples have a right to marry|work=LGBTQ Nation|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> having crossed the 50% in 2011 and not going below that mark since.<ref>["Same-Sex Marriage Support Solidifies Above 50% in U.S." http://www.gallup.com/poll/162398/sex-marriage-support-solidifies-above.aspx] (see graph.)</ref>

==History==
{{Main|History of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
{{See also|Timeline of same-sex marriage in the United States}}

The movement to obtain [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|civil marriage rights]] and benefits for same-sex couples in the United States began in the 1970s.<ref name="Gumbel"/> In the 1971 case ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', the Minnesota Supreme Court ruled that denying marriage licenses to same-sex couples did not violate the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]]. On appeal, the United States Supreme Court denied to hear the case, establishing it as a federal [[precedent]] as it came from mandatory appellate review. The issue did not become prominent in U.S. politics until the 1993 [[Hawaii Supreme Court]] decision in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]'' that declared that state's prohibition to be unconstitutional.<ref>{{cite web|title=Same Sex Marriage Laws – History|url=http://www.ncsl.org/issues-research/human-services/same-sex-marriage-laws.aspx|publisher=National Conference of State Legislatures|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref>

During the 21st century, while [[Timeline of same-sex marriage|several countries]] elsewhere in the world were opening marriage for same-sex couples, public support in the U.S. for same-sex marriage has grown considerably,<ref name="columbia.edu">{{cite journal|url=http://www.columbia.edu/~jrl2124/Lax_Phillips_Gay_Policy_Responsiveness_2009.pdf|title=Gay Rights in the States: Public Opinion and Policy Responsiveness|format=PDF|pages=67–86| doi=10.1017/S0003055409990050| date=August 2009| journal=American Political Science Review|volume=103|issue=3| accessdate=December 20, 2011|first=JEFFREY R.|last=LAX}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Silver|first=Nate|title=Support for Gay Marriage Outweighs Opposition in Polls |url=http://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/09/support-for-gay-marriage-outweighs-opposition-in-polls/ |accessdate=October 28, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 9, 2012}}</ref> and national polls conducted since 2011 show that a majority of Americans support legalizing it. However at the same time, many states also passed bans against same-sex marriage, either legislatively or by [[referendum]].<ref>[https://gaymarriage.procon.org/view.resource.php?resourceID=004857 State-by-State History of Banning and Legalizing Gay Marriage, 1994-2015]</ref> On May 17, 2004, [[Same-sex marriage in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]] became the first U.S. state and the sixth jurisdiction in the world to legalize same-sex marriage following the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court|Supreme Judicial Court]]'s decision in ''[[Goodridge v. Department of Public Health]]'' six months earlier.<ref name="festive">{{cite news|last=Belluck|first=Oam|title=With Festive Mood, Gay Weddings Begin in Massachusetts |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/05/17/national/17CND-GAYS.html |accessdate=January 11, 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 17, 2004}}</ref> On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama became the first sitting U.S. President to publicly declare support for the legalization of same-sex marriage.<ref name="obamasupport-ABCNews">{{cite news |title=Obama Affirms Support for Same-Sex Marriage |url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/video/obama-sex-marriage-legal-16312904|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=May 9, 2012}}</ref> On November 6, 2012, Maine, Maryland and Washington became the first states to legalize same-sex marriage through popular vote.

In June 2013, the Supreme Court ruled in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'' that federal law could not treat as unequal, marriages that individual states had created as equally valid, when it overturned a key provision of the ''[[Defense of Marriage Act]]'' (DOMA), thus forcing federal recognition of same-sex marriage and marriage-related benefits when related to a same-sex marriage performed by a state that sanctioned such marriages. In the two years following ''Windsor'', U.S. district courts in 27 states{{efn|The rulings striking down same-sex marriage bans are from U.S. district courts in the following states: [[Same-sex marriage in Utah#Lawsuit|Utah]],<ref name="Watkins, Tom">{{cite news |last=Watkins |first=Tom|title=In Utah, judge's ruling ignites same-sex marriage frenzy |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/12/20/justice/utah-same-sex-marriage-ruling/| accessdate=December 23, 2013 |newspaper=CNN| date=December 20, 2013}}</ref> [[Bishop v. United States|Oklahoma]],<ref name="chicagotribune1">{{cite news|last=Brandes|first=Heide|title=U.S. judge rules Oklahoma gay marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/sns-rt-us-usa-gaymarriage-oklahoma-20140114,0,7810387.story |accessdate=January 15, 2014|agency=Reuters|work=Chicago Tribune|date=January 14, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Virginia#Bostic v. Schaefer|Virginia]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Simpson|first= Ian|title= Federal judge strikes down Virginia's ban on gay marriage |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/14/us-usa-gaymarriage-virginia-idUSBREA1D05B20140214|accessdate=February 27, 2014 |newspaper=Reuters|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Texas#De Leon v. Perry|Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Calkins|first= Laurel|title= Texas Gay-Marriage Ban Held Illegal as Judge Delays Order|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-02-26/texas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional-federal-judge-says.html|accessdate=February 27, 2014 |newspaper=Bloomberg|date=February 27, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Michigan#DeBoer v. Snyder|Michigan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ww2.lgbtqnation.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Friedman-Michigan-Decision.pdf|title=Deboer v. Snyder: Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law |publisher=United States District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan Southern Division |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=March 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Idaho#Federal lawsuit|Idaho]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Staff reports|title=Federal court strikes down Idaho gay marriage ban|url=http://www.lgbtqnation.com/2014/05/federal-court-strikes-down-idaho-ban-on-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=May 13, 2014|newspaper=LGBTQ Nation|date=May 13, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Oregon#Federal lawsuit|Oregon]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Federal judge strikes down Oregon's same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/19/us/oregon-same-sex-marriage/|publisher=CNN|date=May 19, 2014|accessdate=July 21, 2014|first=Bill|last=Mears |first2=Catherine|last2=Shoichet}}</ref> [[Whitewood v. Corbett|Pennsylvania]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/judge-strikes-down-pennsylvania-same-sex-marriage-ban-n110061|title=Judge Strikes Down Pennsylvania Same-Sex Marriage Ban|publisher=[[NBC News]]|first=Pete |last=Williams|date=May 20, 2014|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in South Dakota|South Dakota]],<ref name=SDruling>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin|title=Federal judge overturns South Dakota same-sex marriage ban|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2015/01/federal-judge-overturns-south-dakota-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=January 12, 2015|work=Metro Weekly|date=January 12, 2015}}</ref> [[Wolf v. Walker|Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/06/06/wisconsin-same-sex-marriage/10093565/ | title=Judge strikes down Wisconsin same-sex marriage ban | publisher=[[USA Today]] | agency=Associated Press | date=June 6, 2014 | accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Indiana#Baskin v. Bogan|Indiana]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-nn-judge-strikes-down-indiana-ban-on-gay-marriage-20140625-story.html |title=Judge strikes down Indiana's ban on gay marriage | newspaper=Los Angeles Times | author=Javier Panzar | date=June 25, 2014 | accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Kentucky#Bourke v. Beshear / Love v. Beshear|Kentucky]],<ref name="wolfson-ky">{{cite news |last1=Wolfson |first1=Andrew|title=Gays have right to marry in Kentucky, judge rules |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/local/2014/07/01/gays-right-marry-kentucky-judge-rules/11900313/ |accessdate=July 1, 2014|work=The Courier-Journal |date=July 1, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Colorado#Burns v. Hickenlooper|Colorado]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/judge-strikes-gay-marriage-ban-stays-ruling-24687448|title=Judge Strikes Down Gay Marriage Ban, Stays Ruling|accessdate=July 23, 2014|publisher=[[ABC News]] |agency=Associated Press|date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Florida]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Rothaus |first=Steve|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2014/08/21/4301754/federal-judge-florida-gay-marriage.html |title=Federal judge: Florida gay-marriage ban unconstitutional |accessdate=August 21, 2014|newspaper=Miami Herald|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in North Carolina#General Synod of the United Church of Christ v. Cooper|North Carolina]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin |title=Federal judge strikes down North Carolina same-sex marriage ban |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/federal-judge-strikes-down-north-carolina-same-sex-marriage-ban/|accessdate=October 10, 2014|work=Metro Weekly|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Alaska#Hamby v. Parnell|Alaska]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boots |first1=Michelle Theriault|title=Federal judge rules Alaska's same-sex marriage ban unconstitutional |url=http://www.adn.com/article/20141012/federal-judge-rules-alaskas-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional|accessdate=October 13, 2014|work=Alaska Dispatch News|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Arizona#Connolly v. Jeanes|Arizona]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liptak|first1=Adam|title=Alaska and Arizona Are Latest to Clear Way for Gay Marriage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/18/us/alaska-gay-marriage.html|accessdate=January 26, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Wyoming|Wyoming]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Order |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/243372518/2-14-cv-00200-44-Wyoming-Injuntion|website=Scribd.com|publisher=U.S. District Court for Wyoming|accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Geidner |first1=Chris |title=Federal Judge Strikes Down Kansas Same-Sex Marriage Ban On Election Day|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/federal-judge-strikes-down-kansas-same-sex-marriage-ban-on-e |accessdate=November 4, 2014|publisher=BuzzFeed News|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in Missouri|Missouri]],<ref name="Geidner">{{cite news|publisher=BuzzFeed News|first=Chris|last=Geidner|date=November 7, 2014|accessdate=November 7, 2014 |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/missouris-same-sex-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional-federal| title=Missouri's Same-Sex Marriage Ban Is Unconstitutional, Federal Judge Rules}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in West Virginia|West Virginia]],<ref name="Herald-Dispatch">{{cite news |last1=Johnson|first1=Curtis|title=Fed judge declares W.Va. marriage ban unconstitutional|url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/breaking/x1231755243/Fed-judge-declares-W-Va-marriage-ban-unconstitutional|accessdate=November 7, 2014|work=Herald-Dispatch |date=November 7, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in South Carolina|South Carolina]],<ref name=SCstrike>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Chris|title=Judge strikes down South Carolina ban on same-sex marriage |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/11/12/judge-strikes-south-carolina-ban-sex-marriage/|accessdate=November 12, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in Montana|Montana]],<ref name=bladeMT>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/11/19/judge-strikes-montana-ban-sex-marriage/|title=Judge strikes down Montana ban on same-sex marriage |accessdate=November 19, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> Arkansas,<ref name=buzzAK>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Arkansas Same-Sex Marriage Ban Is Unconstitutional, Federal Judge Rules|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/arkansas-same-sex-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional-federal-j|accessdate=November 25, 2014|publisher=BuzzFeed News|date=November 25, 2014}}</ref> Mississippi,<ref name=buzzMS>{{cite news|last1=Geidner|first1=Chris|title=Mississippi's Same-Sex Marriage Ban Is Unconstitutional, Federal Judge Rules |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/mississippis-same-sex-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional-feder |accessdate=November 25, 2014|publisher=BuzzFeed News|date=November 25, 2014}}</ref> [[LGBT rights in South Dakota#Rosenbrahn v. Daugaard|South Dakota]],<ref>{{cite news|title=South Dakota: Ban on Gay Marriage Is Struck Down|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/13/us/south-dakota-ban-on-gay-marriage-is-struck-down-.html|accessdate=January 26, 2015|work=The New York Times|agency=Associated Press|date=January 12, 2015}}</ref> and [[Same-sex marriage in Alabama#Searcy v. Strange|Alabama]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mendoza|first1=Jessica|title=Judge strikes down Alabama gay marriage ban: Three things to know|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/USA-Update/2015/0124/Judge-strikes-down-Alabama-gay-marriage-ban-Three-things-to-know-video|accessdate=January 26, 2015|work=The Christian Science Monitor|date=January 24, 2015}}</ref>}} and state courts in six states,{{efn|The cases (and states) are: ''[[Wright v. Arkansas]]'' (Arkansas),<ref>{{cite news|last=DeMillo|first=Andrew|title=Arkansas Judge Strikes Down Gay Marriage Ban|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/arkansas-judge-strikes-down-gay-marriage-ban|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=May 9, 2014}}</ref> ''[[In re Marriage of J.B. and H.B.]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Texas#In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.|In the Matter of the Marriage of A.L.F.L. and K.L.L.]]'' (Texas),<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuffner|first=Charles|title=State court rules gay marriage ban is unconstitutional |url=http://blog.chron.com/kuffsworld/2014/04/state-court-rules-gay-marriage-ban-is-unconstitutional/|newspaper=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=May 11, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Same-sex marriage in Colorado#Brinkman v. Long|Brinkman v. Long]]'' (Colorado),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Steffen|first1=Jordan|title=Adams judge tosses Colorado gay marriage ban but stays ruling |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_26118709/adams-judge-tosses-colorado-gay-marriage-ban-but|work=[[The Denver Post]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Pareto v. Ruvin]]'' and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Florida|Huntsman v. Heavilin]]'' (Florida),<ref>{{cite news|last1=Associated Press|title=Ruling allows same-sex marriages for Florida Keys|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/07/17/gay-same-sex-marriage-florida-keys/12786169/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=July 17, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Same-sex marriage in Louisiana|In Re Costanza and Brewer]]'' (Louisiana),<ref name=buzzfeed20140922>{{cite news |publisher=BuzzFeed News|date=September 22, 2014|accessdate=September 22, 2014|first=Chris |last=Geidner |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/chrisgeidner/louisiana-judge-rules-same-sex-marriage-ban-unconstitutional |title= Louisiana Judge Rules Same-Sex Marriage Ban Unconstitutional, Clashing With Federal Court}}</ref> and ''[[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|State v. Florida]]'' (Missouri).}} plus one state court ruling addressing only the recognition of same-sex marriages from other jurisdictions,{{efn|''[[LGBT rights in Missouri|Barrier v. Vasterling]]'', [[Missouri Circuit Courts|Missouri Circuit Court, 16th Judicial Circuit]]<ref name="Washington Blade">{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=Judge orders Missouri to recognize same-sex marriages |url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/10/03/judge-orders-missouri-recognize-sex-marriages/|accessdate=October 3, 2014 |work=Washington Blade|date=October 3, 2014}}</ref>}} found that same-sex marriage bans violate the [[Constitution of the United States|U.S. Constitution]], while two U.S. district courts{{efn|''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'' (Louisiana), ''[[LGBT rights in Puerto Rico#Court cases|Conde v. Rius]]'' (Puerto Rico)<ref>{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Federal judge upholds La. gay-marriage ban|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/09/03/gay-marriage-louisiana/15021785 |accessdate=September 3, 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>}} and one state court{{efn|''[[Recognition of same-sex unions in Tennessee#State lawsuit|''Borman v. Pyles-Borman'']]'' (Tennessee)}} found that they did not. The flow of federal appeal cases rejecting same-sex marriage bans was finally interrupted in November 2014. In contrast to all other [[Same-sex marriage by Circuit Court|circuits]] that had ruled at the time, the [[Same-sex marriage in the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit]] ruled such bans to be constitutional. The panel ruling reversed six U.S. district court rulings that had found bans on same-sex marriage or its recognition to be unconstitutional, reinstating State bans in the four states served by that circuit ([[Kentucky]], [[Michigan]], [[Ohio]] and [[Tennessee]]).{{efn|The cases reversed (and affected states) are: ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'' and ''[[Love v. Beshear]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Kentucky|Kentucky]]), ''[[DeBoer v. Snyder]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Michigan|Michigan]]), ''[[Obergefell v. Himes]]'' and ''[[Henry v. Himes]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Ohio|Ohio]]), and ''[[Tanco v. Haslam]]'' ([[Same-sex marriage in Tennessee|Tennessee]]).}}<ref name="Thomaston">{{cite news|last=Thomaston|first=Scottie|title=Sixth Circuit upholds same-sex marriage bans|url=http://equalityontrial.com/2014/11/06/sixth-circuit-upholds-sex-marriage-bans/|accessdate=November 6, 2014|date=November 6, 2014}}</ref>

[[File:Obergefell v. Hodges Decision Announced at the Supreme Court of the United States, June 26, 2015.jpg|thumb|upright=1.40|right|The crowd assembled in front of the Supreme Court shortly before same-sex marriage bans were struck down nationwide in ''Obergefell v. Hodges''.]]
On January 16, 2015, the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to hear four cases, on appeal from the Sixth Circuit, on whether states may constitutionally ban same-sex marriages or refuse to recognize such marriages legally performed in another state. The cases were: ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' (Ohio), ''[[Tanco v. Haslam]]'' (Tennessee), ''[[DeBoer v. Snyder]]'' (Michigan), and ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'' (Kentucky). Decided by the court under the heading of ''Obergefell'' on June 26, 2015, a 5–4 majority of justices led by Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] reversed the Sixth Circuit's upholding of state bans and declared that the Court's rulings must evolve in the light of better understanding of discrimination and the constitutional protections available to protect minorities, and that same-sex couples have the constitutional rights to marry and to have their marriages recognized.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/same-sex-marraige-legal-nationwide-supreme-court-rules-n375551|title=Landmark: Supreme Court Rules Same-Sex Marriage Legal Nationwide|first=Pete|last=Williams|date=June 26, 2015|accessdate=June 26, 2015|agency=NBC News}}</ref> ''Obergefell'' therefore overturned the Court's own prior ruling in ''Baker''.

==Before ''Obergefell''==
{{Map of same-sex marriage in the United States prior to Obergefell|align=right|size=400px}}
Prior to ''Obergefell'', [[same-sex marriage]] was legal to at least some degree in thirty-eight states, one territory ([[Same-sex marriage in Guam|Guam]]) and the [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|District of Columbia]]; of the states, [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|Missouri]], [[Same-sex marriage in Kansas|Kansas]], and [[Same-sex marriage in Alabama|Alabama]] had restrictions. Until ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', it was only legal in 12 states and [[Washington D.C.]]. Beginning in July 2013, over forty federal and state courts cited ''Windsor'' to strike down state bans on the licensing or recognition of same-sex marriage. [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|Missouri]] recognized same-sex marriages from out of state and same-sex marriages licensed by the [[St. Louis|City of St. Louis]] under two separate [[Same-sex marriage in Missouri|state court orders]]; two other jurisdictions issued such licenses as well. In [[Kansas]], marriage licenses were available to same-sex couples in most counties, but the state did not recognize their validity. Some counties in [[Alabama]] issued marriage licenses to same-sex couples for three weeks until the [[Supreme Court of Alabama|state Supreme Court]] ordered probate judges to stop doing so. That court's ruling did not address the recognition of same-sex marriages already licensed in Alabama, but referred to them as "purported 'marriage licenses{{' "}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Petition Granted|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/257589071/1140460-Petition-Granted|website=Scribd.com|publisher=Supreme Court of Alabama|accessdate=March 24, 2015|page=27}}</ref> In two additional states, same-sex marriages were previously legal between the time their bans were struck down and then [[Stay of proceedings#United States|stayed]]. [[Same-sex marriage in Michigan|Michigan]] recognized the validity of more than 300 marriage licenses issued to same-sex couples and those marriages. [[Same-sex marriage in Arkansas|Arkansas]] recognized the more than 500 marriage licenses issued to same-sex couples there,<ref>{{cite news|last1=DeMillo|first1=Andrew|title=Judge: Arkansas Must Recognize in-State Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/judge-arkansas-recognize-state-sex-marriages-31648493|accessdate=June 9, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=June 9, 2015}}</ref> and the Federal Government had not taken a position on Arkansas's marriage licenses.

==Legal issues==
{{See also|Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States}}

The legal issues surrounding same-sex marriage in the United States are determined by the nation's [[federalism|federal]] system of government, in which the [[Status (law)|status]] of a person, including marital status, is determined in large measure by the individual states. Prior to 1996, the Federal Government did not define marriage; any marriage recognized by a [[U.S. state|state]] was recognized by the Federal Government, even if that marriage was not recognized by one or more states, as was the case until 1967 with interracial marriage, which some states [[anti-miscegenation laws|banned by statute]].

[[File:Same-sex marriage in San Francisco City Hall 20080617.jpg|thumb|left|Civil [[same-sex marriage]] ceremony being performed in [[San Francisco]] [[San Francisco City Hall|City Hall]] in June 2008.]]

Prior to 2004, same-sex marriage was not performed in any U.S. jurisdiction. It was subsequently legalized in different jurisdictions through legislation, court rulings,<ref name="Adams & Crary March 11, 2009">Glenn Adams and David Crary, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8789627 "Maine voters reject gay-marriage law"], November 4, 2009</ref> tribal council rulings,<ref name="LittleTraverseBayBand">{{cite news|last=Houston|first=Sonya|title=Tribe marries same-sex couple but state won't recognize it|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/03/17/politics/michigan-same-sex-marriage/index.html?hpt=hp_c5|accessdate=March 18, 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=March 17, 2013}}</ref> and popular vote in referenda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/07/14978747-for-first-time-voters-back-gay-marriage-in-statewide-votes?lite|title=For first time, voters back gay marriage in statewide votes|publisher=NBC News|date=|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/02/01/10294578-washington-state-senate-approves-same-sex-marriage-bill|title=Washington State Senate approves same-sex marriage|publisher=MSNBC|date=February 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name="The Keweenaw Report">{{cite web|url=http://www.keweenawreport.com/news/kbic-council-shake-up-casino-plan-rejected/|title=KBIC Council Shake-Up; Casino Plan Rejected |publisher=The Keweenaw Report |date=December 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>

The Supreme Court's ruling in ''Obergefell'' renders moot any remaining legal challenges, as it specifically orders states to both issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples, and to recognize as valid marriages performed in other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/06/gay-marriage-supreme-court-decision-119463.html|title=Supreme Court gay marriage decision: Full text of Obergefell ruling|newspaper=Politico|date=June 26, 2015}}</ref>

===Federal law===
According to the Federal Government's [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) in 2004, [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|more than 1,138 rights and protections]] are conferred to U.S. citizens upon marriage by the Federal Government; areas affected include [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits, veterans' benefits, health insurance, [[Medicaid]], hospital visitation, estate taxes, retirement savings, pensions, [[family leave]], and immigration law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d04353r.pdf|title=2004 updated report of the GAO|format=PDF |date=January 23, 2004|publisher=GAO|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref>

Since July 9, 2015, married same-sex couples throughout the United States have equal access to all the federal benefits that married opposite-sex couples have.<ref name="lynch">{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-lynch-announces-federal-marriage-benefits-available-same-sex-couples|title=Attorney General Lynch Announces Federal Marriage Benefits Available to Same-Sex Couples Nationwide|date=July 9, 2015|publisher=Department of Justice|author=Loretta Lynch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110003040/https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-lynch-announces-federal-marriage-benefits-available-same-sex-couples|archivedate=10 November 2016}}</ref>

The ''[[Defense of Marriage Act]]'' (DOMA) was enacted in 1996. DOMA's Section 2 says that no state needs to recognize the legal validity of a same-sex relationship even if recognized as marriage by another state. It purports to relieve a state of its reciprocal obligation to honor the laws of other states as required by the Constitution's [[full faith and credit clause]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wermiel|first1=Stephen|title=SCOTUS for law students: The Defense of Marriage Act and the Constitution|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2012/03/scotus-for-law-students-the-defense-of-marriage-act-and-the-constitution-sponsored-by-bloomberg-law/|accessdate=September 23, 2014|publisher=SCOTUSblog |date=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Even before DOMA, however, states sometimes refused to recognize a marriage from another jurisdiction if it was counter to its "strongly held public policies".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolff|first1=Tobias Barrington|title=DOMA Repeal and the Truth About Full Faith & Credit |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tobias-barrington-wolff/doma-repeal-and-the-truth_b_905484.html |accessdate=September 23, 2014|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=July 21, 2011}}</ref> Most lawsuits that seek to require a state to recognize a marriage established in another jurisdiction argue on the basis of [[equal protection clause|equal protection]] and [[due process clause|due process]], not the full faith and credit clause.{{efn|Among many examples: (1) the U.S. District Court ruling in ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'', which required Kentucky to recognize same-sex marriages from Canada and several U.S. states, was decided on equal protection grounds alone. The plaintiffs claimed that Kentucky's ban violated the full faith and credit clause, but the court found it unnecessary to address that argument.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/206724639/GREGORY-BOURKE-et-al-V-STEVE-BESHEAR-et-al |title=Memorandum Opinion, ''Bouke v. Beshear''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Western District of Kentucky |date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> and (2) the plaintiffs in ''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'', who sought Louisiana's recognition of their out-of-state marriages, argued only on the basis of equal protection and due process. One of the Louisiana statutes they challenged made clear the state's assertion of its right to deny recognition to the legal act of another state: "A purported marriage between persons of the same sex violates a ''strong public policy'' of the state of Louisiana". (emphasis added)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/238549858/2-13-cv-05090-131 |title=Order and Reasons, ''Robicheaux v. Caldwell''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Louisiana |date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>}}

DOMA's Section 3 defined marriage for the purposes of federal law as a union of one man and one woman.<ref>{{usc|1|7}}.</ref> It was challenged in the [[United States federal courts|federal courts]]. On July 8, 2010, Judge [[Joseph Louis Tauro|Joseph Tauro]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District Court of Massachusetts]] held that the denial of federal rights and benefits to lawfully married Massachusetts same-sex couples is unconstitutional under the [[equal protection clause]] of the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]].<ref name="hrc.org">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09marriage.html|title=Judge Topples U.S. Rejection of Gay Unions|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=June 2, 2011|first1=Abby |last1=Goodnough |first2=John|last2=Schwartz}}</ref> Beginning in 2010, eight federal courts found DOMA Section 3 unconstitutional in cases involving bankruptcy, public employee benefits, estate taxes, and immigration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/states/entry/c/doma|title=The Defense of Marriage Act|publisher=Freedom to Marry |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/31/doma-unconstitutional-ruling-appeals-court-boston_n_1559031.html|title=DOMA Ruled Unconstitutional By Federal Appeals Court |last=Lavoie |first=Denise |date=May 31, 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewstates.org/projects/stateline/headlines/defense-of-marriage-act-discriminates-against-gays-federal-court-rules-85899424320|title=Defense of Marriage Act Discriminates Against Gays, Federal Court Rules|last=Malewitz|first=Jim|date=October 18, 2012 |publisher=Pewstates.org|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> On October 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit Court of Appeals]] became the first court to hold sexual orientation to be a [[suspect classification|quasi-suspect classification]] and applied [[intermediate scrutiny]] to strike down Section 3 of DOMA as unconstitutional in ''[[Windsor v. United States]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tiven|first=Rachel|title=Edie Wins! Another Ruling Against DOMA, What It Means|url=http://www.immigrationequality.org/2012/10/edie-wins-another-ruling-against-doma-what-it-means/|publisher=[[Immigration Equality (organization)]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in ''Windsor'' on June 26, 2013, that Section 3 violated the Fifth Amendment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Live Analysis of the Supreme Court Decisions on Gay Marriage |url=http://projects.nytimes.com/live-dashboard/2013-06-26-supreme-court-gay-marriage|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>{{efn|Other cases that sought review by the U.S. Supreme Court were ''[[Golinski v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Gill v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Massachusetts v. United States Department of Health and Human Services]]'', and ''[[Pedersen v. Office of Personnel Management]]''.}}

As a result of the ''Windsor'' decision, married same-sex couples—regardless of domicile—have federal tax benefits (including the ability to file joint federal income tax returns), military benefits, federal employment benefits, and immigration benefits.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michon|first1=Kathleen|title=Federal Marriage Benefits Available to Same-Sex Couples |url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/same-sex-couples-federal-marriage-benefits-30326.html|accessdate=July 26, 2014 |publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Laurence |first1=Beth|title=Military Benefits for Same-Sex Spouses Post-DOMA|url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/military-benefits-same-sex-spouses-post-doma.html|publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all|accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wadsworth|first1=Margaret|title=Veterans Benefits for Same-Sex Spouses Post-DOMA|url=http://www.nolo.com/legal-encyclopedia/veterans-benefits-same-sex-spouses-post-doma.html|publisher=Nolo.com a.k.a. Nolo Law for all |accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Kerry Announces Visa Changes for Same-Sex Couples |url=http://blogs.usembassy.gov/malaysia/2013/08/05/john-kerry-announces-visa-changes-for-same-sex-couples/ |publisher=U.S. Embassy Kuala Lumpur|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=August 2, 2013}}</ref> In February 2014, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] expanded federal recognition of same-sex marriages to include bankruptcies, prison visits, survivor benefits and refusing to testify against a spouse.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perez |first1=Evan|title=U.S. expands legal benefits, services for same-sex marriages|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/02/08/politics/holder-same-sex-marriage-rights/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> Likewise in June 2014, family [[medical leave]] benefits under the ''Family Medical Leave Act 1975'' were extended to married same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chappell |first1=Bill|title=Married Same-Sex Couples To Receive More Federal Benefits |url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/06/20/323855724/same-sex-couples-across-u-s-to-receive-broader-benefits |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |publisher=NPR |date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> With respect to [[social security]] and veterans benefits, same-sex married couples are eligible for full benefits from the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]] (VA) and the [[Social Security Administration]] (SSA). Prior to the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' on June 26, 2015, the VA and SSA could provide only limited benefits to married same-sex couples living in states where same-sex marriage was not legal.<ref name="Guardian20140620">{{cite news|last1=Glenza|first1=Jessica|title=Federal agencies roll out benefits for married same-sex couples|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/20/same-sex-couples-benefits-expanded-obama-administration |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Capehart|first1=Jonathan|title=Fix the Social Security discrepancy DOMA left behind |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-partisan/wp/2014/05/09/fix-the-social-security-discrepancy-doma-left-behind/ |accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> Effective March 27, 2015, the definition of spouse under the ''[[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Forman|first1=Shira|title=DOL Issues Final Rule Amending FMLA Definition of "Spouse" to Include Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/dol-issues-final-rule-amending-fmla-definition-spouse-to-include-same-sex-marriages|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=Sheppard Mullin Richter & Hampton LLP|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> includes employees in a same-sex marriage regardless of state of residence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Trotier|first1=Geoffrey S.|title=FMLA "Spouse" Definition Now Includes Same-Sex Spouses and Common-Law Spouses|journal=The National Law Review|date=February 24, 2015|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-spouse-definition-now-includes-same-sex-spouses-and-common-law-spouses|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=von Briesen & Roper, s.c}}</ref> Following the ''Obergefell'' decision, the Justice Department extended all federal marriage benefits to married same-sex couples nationwide.<ref name="lynch"/>

The Federal Government recognizes the marriages of same-sex couples who married in certain states in which same-sex marriage was legal for brief periods between the time a court order allowed such couples to marry and that court order was stayed, including [[Michigan]]. The Federal Government also recognized marriages performed in [[Utah]] from December 20, 2013 to January 6, 2014, even while the state didn't. Under similar circumstances, the Federal Government never took a position on [[Indiana]] or [[Wisconsin]]'s marriages performed in brief periods, though it did recognize them once the respective states announced they would do so. It had not taken a position with respect to similar marriages in [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=DOJ pressured to recognize same-sex marriages in 3 states|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/09/19/doj-pressured-recognize-sex-marriages-3-states/|accessdate=September 24, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> prior to the ''Obergefell'' decision legalizing and recognizing same-sex marriages in all 50 states.

Opponents of same-sex marriage have worked to prevent individual states from recognizing same-sex unions by attempting to amend the United States Constitution to define marriage as a union between one man and one woman. In 2006, the ''[[Federal Marriage Amendment]]'', which would prohibit states from recognizing same-sex marriages, was approved by the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] on a party-line vote and was debated by the full Senate, but was ultimately defeated in both houses of Congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511145406/http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html|title=Senate blocks same-sex marriage ban|publisher=CNN|date=June 7, 2006|archivedate=May 11, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2006}}</ref> On April 2, 2014, the Alabama State House adopted a resolution calling for a [[Convention to propose amendments to the United States Constitution|constitutional convention]] to propose an amendment to ban same-sex marriage nationwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140402/NEWS/304020079/Alabama-House-approves-call-put-same-sex-marriage-ban-U-S-Constitution |title=Alabama House approves call to put same-sex marriage ban in U.S. Constitution |work=Montgomery Advertiser |date=April 2, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412171146/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140402/NEWS/304020079/Alabama-House-approves-call-put-same-sex-marriage-ban-U-S-Constitution |archivedate=April 12, 2014 }}</ref>

===State and territorial recognition===
{{Further|Same-sex marriage law in the United States by state}}
Same-sex marriages are licensed in and recognized by all U.S. states and [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]], as well as all U.S. territories except [[LGBT rights in American Samoa|American Samoa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/samesex-marriage-american-samoa-may-be-the-only-territory-in-the-us-where-the-historic-supreme-court-ruling-does-not-apply-10379804.html|title=Same-sex marriage: American Samoa may be the only territory in the US where the historic Supreme Court ruling does not apply|work=The Independent|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> On July 3, 2015, the Attorney General for American Samoa stated "we are reviewing the opinion [''Obergefell v. Hodges''] and its potential applicability to American Samoa, and will provide comment when it is completed."<ref>http://www.samoanews.com/content/en/ag-reviews-supreme-court’s-same-sex-marriage-ruling</ref> On January 6, 2016, Alabama's Chief Justice, [[Roy Moore]], issued a ruling forbidding state officials from issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref name="RoyMoore">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/alabama-chief-justice-orders-halt-gay-marriage-n491521|title=Alabama Chief Justice Orders Halt to Gay Marriage|first=Pete|last=Williams|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> The ruling had no effect and all Alabama counties continued either issuing marriage licenses to all couples or not issue licenses at all, and in May 2016 Moore was charged with ethics violations by the state Judicial Inquiry Commission for the ruling,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alabama-gaymarriage-idUSKCN0XY042|title=Alabama's top judge faces ethics charges over gay-marriage order|work=Reuters|date=7 May 2016}}</ref> subsequently being suspended from the bench for the remainder of his term on September 30 of that year.<ref name="almedgrp">{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/birmingham/index.ssf/2016/09/alabama_supreme_court_chief_ju.html|title=Alabama Supreme Court Chief Justice Roy Moore suspended for rest of term|publisher=Alabama Media Group|first=Kent|last=Faulk|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=September 30, 2016}}</ref>

====Counties not issuing marriage licenses====
[[File:Same-sex marriage in Texas by county, August 2015.png|180px|thumb|As of June 20, 2017, only Irion county (pink) refuses licenses to same-sex couples.<ref name="Ballotpedia">{{cite web|title=Local government responses to Obergefell v. Hodges|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Local_government_responses_to_Obergefell_v._Hodges#tab=Texas|website=ballotpedia.org|date=July 1, 2015 – June 26, 2017}}</ref>]]
[[File:Counties.png|180px|thumb|Counties issuing marriage licenses to all couples (blue) and counties issuing to no one (grey) as of June 2017]]
Officials of nine counties in two states, [[Same-sex marriage in Texas|Texas]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Alabama|Alabama]], are still  unwilling to issue licenses to same-sex couples as of June 2017. Those wishing to marry within the state must travel to another part of the state in order to obtain a license. However, some counties may require at least one person to be a resident of the county in order to receive a marriage license.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://altoday.com/archives/17555-two-years-later-7-alabama-counties-still-not-issuing-marriage-licences-sex-couples|title=2yrs later, 7co. still not issuing same-sex marriage licenses|date=2017-06-29|work=Alabama Today|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US}}</ref>
